s discovered how to create very dilute atomic or molecular gases, cooled first by laser cooling and then by evaporative cooling . [ 15 ] They are trapped using magnetic fields or optical dipole potentials in ultrahigh vacuum chambers. Isotopes which have been used include rubidium (Rb-87 and Rb-85), strontium (Sr-87, Sr-86, and Sr-84) potassium (K-39 and K-40), sodium (Na-23), lithium (Li-7 and Li-6), and hydrogen (H-1). The temperatures to which they can be cooled are as low as a few nanokelvin. The developments have been very fast in the past few years. A team of NIST and the University of Colorado has succeeded in creating and observing vortex quantization in these systems. [ 16 ] The concentration of vortices increases with the angular velocity of the rotation, similar to the case of superfluid helium and superconductivity. Mechanical systems [ edit ] Macroscopic quantum effects have been observed in the motion of engineered mechanical objects. [ 17 ] Research in the field of quantum optomechanics focuses on the manipulation of the quantized vibrational states ( phonons ) of mechanical resonators . [ 18 ] Control is realized via two primary experimental architectures. Cavity optomechanics uses laser light in an optical cavity to couple to the motion of objects like mirrors or membranes. [ 19 ] Circuit electromechanics uses superconducting microwave circuits to couple to piezoelectric resonators, typically realized as surface acoustic wave (SAW) or bulk acoustic resonator (BAR) devices. [ 20 ] Both architectures have been used to cool massive resonators to their quantum ground state . [ 21 ] [ 22 ] A landmark experiment in 2010, using an electromechanical system, was the first to demonstrate the deterministic preparation of non-classical states in a mechanical resonator. [ 21 ] This work achieved cooling to the quantum ground state ( n = 0 {\displaystyle n=0} ), preparation of a single-phonon Fock state ( n = 1 {\displaystyle n=1} ), and the generation of a quant